text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Association of Indian Accent with the Nerdy Character%0a:Author: SubhasishM%0a:Original: [[Articles.TheIndianAccentInMedia|TheIndianAccentInMedia]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sanjana_m|sanjana_m]]%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 17:06%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-020956-625470#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 19:09-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-020956-625470#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI think the Indian accent in particular has become associative of a certain character as you mentioned. I was born in India and my parents have their own Bengali accents, but even I have come to associate the stereotypical accent we have on TV with the archetype of character you described.%0a%0aIt's unfortunate that this has become so normalized in our society, and I think it is much more likely that people in America who come across those with the stereotypical Indian accent immediately can assign a character to them. While this phenomenon isn't unique to Indian accents, I think that Indians are one group that are among the most negatively affected by this societal discrimination.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
