diff:1620432414:1620432414:=1,40d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Expansion: Association of Indian Accent with the Nerdy Character%0a%3c :Author: SubhasishM%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.TheIndianAccentInMedia|TheIndianAccentInMedia]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sanjana_m|sanjana_m]]%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 07.05.2021 - 17:06%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I think the Indian accent in particular has become associative of a certain character as you mentioned. I was born in India and my parents have their own Bengali accents, but even I have come to associate the stereotypical accent we have on TV with the archetype of character you described.%0a%3c %0a%3c It's unfortunate that this has become so normalized in our society, and I think it is much more likely that people in America who come across those with the stereotypical Indian accent immediately can assign a character to them. While this phenomenon isn't unique to Indian accents, I think that Indians are one group that are among the most negatively affected by this societal discrimination.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
